This has fixed the issue on iOS for me, that scrolling in Flutter web app opened in Facebook Messenger was closing whole webview. Didn't notice any side effects yet. Thanks a lot!

The proposed fix do not work anymore, but this code at the end of the head will make the browser scrollbar behave properly. 

```html
 <style>
    body {
      height: 200vh !important;
      position: static !important;
    }

    flt-glass-pane {
      position: fixed !important;
    }
  </style>
  ```

Then how to force rendering underneath address bar ?? I can't figure it out...

Referring to an earlier comment I made here: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/69529#issuecomment-1215762415

AFAIK there is no available API from Apple to tell the browser the screen has scrolled some content. Since we are not rendering the browser bar, we do not have control over it. It would be very easy for us to do so if there were a way to communicate that to the platform, but I have looked many times over the years for this specific issue and have not found a way yet.

@yjbanov has suggested some ideas to approach this from the engine above, but I don't know if they have been tried or successful.

@Piinks  got it.

This is just a suggestion, and to be honest I think its maybe one of the only ways to fix it stably;

Either flutter needs to be able to tell the browser what's going (for that all major browsers need to write code to make it happen, which is probably more of a tall ask) or flutter needs to use the browsers the way they were designed to be used, at least until the browsers can be convinced the add this feature, because leaving it in this broken state is not really a solution.

Would it be out of the realm of practicality to change it around?

